06028nam a22006975i 9780822389149DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20082008ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223891497 a10.1515/97808223891492doi  a(DE-B1597)552236  a(OCoLC)1125524118  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aJC423b.N483 2008 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04aThe New Pluralism :bWilliam Connolly and the Contemporary Global Condition /cDavid Campbell, Morton Schoolman. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (372 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION: PLURALISM ''OLD'' AND ''NEW'' -- tA PLURALIST MIND: AGONISTIC RESPECT AND THE PROBLEM OF VIOLENCE TOWARD DIFFERENCE -- tCONNOLLY'S VOICE -- tTHE TIME OF RIGHTS: EMERGENT THOUGHTS IN AN EMERGENCY SETTING -- tVISUALIZING POST-NATIONAL DEMOCRACY -- tUNCERTAIN CONSTELLATIONS: DIGNITY, EQUALITY, RESPECT AND . . . ? -- tPROHIBITION AND TRANSGRESSION -- tRADICALIZING DEMOCRATIC THEORY: SOCIAL SPACE IN CONNOLLY, DELEUZE, AND RANCIÈRE -- tTHEORIZING DYSLEXIA WITH CONNOLLY AND HARAWAY -- tSOVEREIGNTY AND THE RETURN OF THE REPRESSED -- tBECOMING CONNOLLY: CRITIQUE, CROSSING OVER, AND CONCEPTS -- tIDENTITY, DIFFERENCE, AND THE GLOBAL: WILLIAM CONNOLLY'S INTERNATIONAL THEORY -- tAN INTERVIEW WITH WILLIAM CONNOLLY, DECEMBER 2006 -- tBibliography -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWilliam Connolly, one of the best-known and most important political theorists writing today, is a principal architect of the "new pluralism." In this volume, leading thinkers in contemporary political theory and international relations provide a comprehensive investigation of the new pluralism, Connolly's contributions to it, and its influence on the fields of political theory and international relations. Together they trace the evolution of Connolly's ideas, illuminating his challenges to the "old," conventional pluralist theory that dominated American and British political science and sociology in the second half of the twentieth century.The contributors show how Connolly has continually revised his ideas about pluralism to take into account radical changes in global politics, incorporate new theories of cognition, and reflect on the centrality of religion in political conflict. They engage his arguments for an agonistic democracy in which all fundamentalisms become the objects of politicization, so that differences are not just tolerated but are productive of debate and the creative source of a politics of becoming. They also explore the implications of his work, often challenging his views to widen the reach of even his most recently developed theories. Connolly's new pluralism will provoke all citizens who refuse to subordinate their thinking to the regimes in which they reside, to religious authorities tied to the state, or to corporate interests tied to either. The New Pluralism concludes with an interview with Connolly in which he reflects on the evolution of his ideas and expands on his current work.Contributors: Roland Bleiker, Wendy Brown, David Campbell, William Connolly, James Der Derian, Thomas L. Dumm, Kathy E. Ferguson, Bonnie Honig, George Kateb, Morton SchoolmanMichael J. Shapiro, Stephen K. White  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aCultural pluralismxPolitical aspects. 0aDemocracyxPhilosophy. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh1 aHonig, Bonnie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCampbell, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov